    name: "Volunteer Care During Time of Serving Refugees",
    subject: "Volunteer Care During Time of Serving Refugees",
    body: "Dear    Lester Glick      , \n \n\n   We are writing to you as your loved one embarks on a journey with i58 Global, serving as a volunteer in refugee ministry for the next three months. We understand that entrusting someone you care deeply about to our care is a significant decision, and we want to assure you that we take the responsibility of providing a supportive and nurturing environment seriously. \n \n\n   At i58 Global, we prioritize team care and accountability to ensure each volunteer has a positive experience while serving with us. We believe in fostering community, accountability, and connection among our volunteers. We seek to do this by providing evening meals (workdays), weekly worship/prayer nights, and Sunday church services to provide spiritual nourishment and fellowship, which varies depending on which field they serve. Additionally, we recognize the importance of personal time for reflection and recharge. Therefore, we set evening curfews and encourage weekly solo time for volunteers to connect with God on a deeper level and to refresh spiritually. \n \n\n   Our on-the-field volunteer care team is dedicated to providing times of personal connection and support to each volunteer. They are available to address any concerns or challenges that may arise. They are committed to ensuring a positive experience that will transition seamlessly back to their home community and church. \n \n\n   As their pastor, we encourage you to stay connected with      {{firstName}}      while serving abroad. Your support and encouragement play a vital role in the journey, and we value the partnership between i58 Global and supporting churches. In turn, we expect volunteers to stay connected with their home churches and respect their home church's standards in the practical application of the Christian life. \n \n\n   It's worth emphasizing that although we aren't a Bible school or church, our volunteers often encounter faith-related challenges as part of their mission experience. However, we view these challenges as valuable opportunities for spiritual growth and personal development. Working alongside a broader community of believers, volunteers gain a broader worldview and firsthand insight into the struggles faced by refugees. Through these experiences, we believe individuals can experience significant positive spiritual growth. We have often seen where these experiences have profoundly impacted or even transformed a volunteer's worldview, and we desire that this could translate into a blessing for their home church and community, ultimately bringing glory to God. \n \n\n   Should any concerns arise during their time with us, we invite open communication with our field leadership. We are here to listen, support, and promptly address any issues or concerns that may arise. \n       Greece:        Nathaniel Shrock, WhatsApp +30 694 691 4352 or        nate@i58global.org     \n       Germany:        Henry Troyer, WhatsApp +1 931 622 8117 or          henry@i58global.org         \n \n\n   Once again, thank you for entrusting your loved one to us. We are committed to providing a safe, nurturing, and transformative experience for each volunteer and look forward to seeing the impact they will make while serving refugees. \n \n\n \n\n   Blessings, \n \n\n     Amos Kauffman   \n   Serving as CEO for i58 Global \n \n     Contact Information   \n   Email:        akauffman@i58global.org     \n   Phone, WhatsApp or Viber: +1-717-475-3551 \n   Website:        i58global.org",
